values.description: A mask of the Swamp Ninjas of the south, it's purpose is unknown, likely it's either a tradition or an intimidation tactic.
Salvaged rags, straps and plates pulled together by a decent craftsman has made this monstrosity. Commonly found on wanderers and bandits, it shouldn't be underestimated.
These actually have hidden chain mail sewn into the lining.  Sneaky.
A solid steel helmet, flared at the sides.
Heavy duty armour commonly worn by government owned samurai.
Heavy armour plates for protecting the neck and face.
A chain undershirt provides a reliable second layer of defence.
A good all-round medium class armour, favoured by any warrior that has to travel across the wilds.
An armoured hood, for some kind of heavy-ninja dude.
Reinforced to pad your legs, turns a potential slice into a nasty bruise.
The best lightweight under-armour that money can buy.  Adds a reliable extra layer of defence to your equipment.
Heavy duty armour commonly worn by government owned samurai.
A regular longcoat with the sleeves removed to provide better cooling for the wearer.  Commonly worn amongst the gangs of the swamps.
Reinforced to pad your legs, turns a potential slice into a nasty bruise.
These actually have hidden chain mail sewn into the lining.  Sneaky.
For when you want to look dapper, even though you're a vagabond.
A chain undershirt provides a reliable second layer of defence.
Heavy duty armour commonly worn by government owned samurai.  Not much good for running around in though.
Standard Holy Army issue.
A reinforced wicker hat.

Head plates were invented by an old forgotten clan that was obsessed with luck.  Before battle they used prophets and shamans to predict where on their head the next fatal blow was due to land, then position the metal plate on their head accordingly.  Sometimes it worked, sometimes it didn't.  Such is luck, they would say.
A simple eye protection for sandstorms, standard issue in the Traders Guild
Dirty rags, worn by slaves and good-for-nothings
Undershirts provide a reliable second layer of defence.
A chain hood.
For when you want to look dapper, even though you're a vagabond.

The only heavy armour that isn't affiliated with any particular faction, it's become standard with mercenaries and short-range wanderers.  
More of a medium-heavy class, it allows a little more versatility than other heavy armours.
Simple bindings to protect the bones of the fist.  Commonly worn by martial artists, those who shun the use of the sword.
A breathing mask that helps mitigate the negative health effects of fog.
Undershirts provide a reliable second layer of defence.
A rough fabric favoured by the Holy Nation for its lack of comfort.
Wear this and you will be a real ninja!  (Warning: Not a substitute for real ninja training)
A plated leather jacket with a good solid armour coverage. Commonly worn by the wealthier drifters and professional adventurer scouts.
Orange robes of the Holy Nation Priest caste, demanding respect from anyone lower than a High Paladin.
Pads your legs, turns a potential slice into a nasty bruise.

This armour is nice and light without hampering mobility, it will protect your heart and that's it. It's designed to be worn over chain or leather armour as an extra layer of protection, although most people don't for some reason.  Probably because they can't afford any.

Head plates were invented by an old forgotten clan that was obsessed with luck.  Before battle their prophets and shamans would predict where on their head the next fatal blow was due to land, then position the metal plate on their head accordingly.  Statistically, some would always turn out to be correct and those lucky ones, by virtue of surviving, would be the ones to return and spread word of the prophet's success, further reinforcing the belief.
Nobody knows why it's called a Police Helmet, as the Samurai Police don't wear these.  Perhaps it's another Old Empire remnant.

The Tin Can is a super heavy-class helmet and makes for the best head protection around.  Heavy cuts and slashes against it will still make your head ring, but at least you will still have your face attached.  Unfortunately the limited field of view does hamper your combat awareness a fair bit.
A cover-up suit popular with theives and ninjas.  Helps cover your visibility and identity.
A chain undershirt provides a reliable second layer of defence.
Some crazy dude at some point must have thought "I like hats, but I don't like helmets, but I also like having a sword-resistant head...".  Now we have iron hats.
Lightweight leather leg protection.
Good solid long-range boots, common amongst travellers.
Traditional heavy duty armour commonly worn by government owned samurai.
These shackles are faulty and don't do a very good job of hindering prisoners.
Un-plated version of Samurai Leg-plate armour.  Nice and light.
Dirty rags usually worn by slaves, beggars and drifters.
Good shirt for sneaking about, doing spy stuff.

Straw hats are common among everyone from peasant farmers to desert scouts and help shade the wearer from the intense heat of the sun.  Shading the eyes from glare can also provide a minor aid in combat.
A solid, heavy helmet with good protection of the face.  Often worn by bandits, as the high face guard also provides some anonymity.

The standard armoured boots, found everywhere.  Commonly left out of an armour set, as drifters don't usually see much likelyhood in getting hit in the shins and prefer the reduced encumbrance of a pair of wooden sandals or even going barefoot altogether.
A long leather coat, offers a light protection from attacks.  Pretty hot to wear in the desert, but popular in the Swamps because of the constant rain.
A hat with a shade for the eyes, favoured by traders.
Heavy duty armour commonly worn by government owned samurai.
A protective hood with steel plates on the sides.
A solid steel helmet with a protective visor.
Keeps the wind and sand out of your face.  Also helps to hide your pasty face in the darkness.

Ragged cloth with plates to protect the sword arm.  It's pretty dire protection, but the wide open mid-section creates an opening that leads to more predictable enemy attacks.  It's lightweight and the arm plates on your forward side allow you to adopt some extra skillful combat tactics.
The best lightweight under-armour that money can buy.  Adds a reliable extra layer of defence to your equipment.
Reinforced to pad your legs, turns a potential slice into a nasty bruise.
A breathing mask that helps mitigate the negative health effects of fog.
Keeps the heat off your head and pads your brains.  It's often worn by slave traders in this style, and has started to become associated as being part of their uniform.
A paladins helmet
A chain undershirt provides a reliable second layer of defence.
Heavy prisoner shackles. They stop you from running and doing a lot of things. They will trip you up in combat. They are locked on, you need to pick the lock somehow.

The Traders Guild is proud of its claimed "rags to riches" origin story, and continues to use the leather wrap-around jacket as its unofficial uniform.  Although, being over 200 years old nobody can confirm the true origins of the Guild, and skeptics say the mundane clothing is just to make them seem more humble and honest, so you don't notice when they are ripping you off.
Undershirts provide a reliable second layer of defence.
A creepy black duster coat worn by wierdos out of the Ashlands.  Provides good protection against the harsh environment.
Keeps sweat and hair out of your eyes.
A rough fabric favoured by the Holy Nation for its lack of comfort.
Once part of a uniform of the Old Empire, it seems to have hung around to this day.
Quite a good head padding in a simple cloth.  It can be wrapped around the face to protect the eyes in a dust storm
For when you want to look dapper, even though you're a vagabond.
Undershirts provide a reliable second layer of defence.
Wear this and you will be a real ninja!  (Warning: Not a substitute for real ninja training)

Salvaged rags, straps and plates pulled together by a decent craftsman has made this monstrosity.  This armour has plenty of gaps and vulnerabilities, but allows good freedom of movement for its class.  Commonly found on wanderers and bandits, but is also favoured by duelists.
A simple woollen hat, good for cold desert nights.
Martial artists are a rare oddity in a world of swords and have a reputation as eccentrics.  They are however the bane of slavers, because they can never be disarmed.
It gives near perfect protection of the body, because it's so holy.  Limb protection is not so great, but at least you'll have your organs.
Some sort of crude helmet patched together out of scraps of plate, with added spikes for intimidation.  Guaranteed to be strapped to a bandit of some kind.
Classical wooden sandals.  They take a bit of getting used to, but they're actually really good for running in sand.
An expensive silk robe made by artisans of the Empire's capital.  Worn by nobles and the wealthy elite as a sign of status.
An expensive silk robe made by artisans of the Empire's capital.  Worn by nobles and the wealthy elite as a sign of status.
Supposedly makes the wearer look a bit like a skeleton.
Black rags typical of down-and-out hobo ninjas
A crude suit made out of human skin, expertly torn off it's original owner in sheets and loosely tied on with wire.  The perfect disguise.
The Skin Bandits need a constant supply of fresh human skin to make new suits, as they tend to rot away quite quickly.
A very heavy iron hat. As with other eye-slit based helmets, it offers fantastic protection but you can't see a damn thing.
Iron shoes that are pretty painful to wear. The Crab Raiders designed this armour with the aim of being more like crabs, with little consideration of other factors.

An exotic suit of heavy armour plates that gives the wearer the toughness and mobility of a big rock.  The Crab Raiders designed this armour with the aim of being more like crabs, but little consideration of other factors.

An exotic suit of heavy armour plates that gives the wearer the toughness and mobility of a big rock.  The Crab Raiders designed this armour with the aim of being more like crabs, with little consideration of other factors.
A metal cage-armoured jacket.
Metal cage-armoured pants.

Tired of weak leather to protect your fat human legs?  Using the latest in the Hives research technology we have positioned metal stuff in no less than TWO key locations for optimal leg stab protection.  Queen-approved!
This is basically just wrapping a strip of chainmail around your head, but it does do a good job of protecting you when it's not falling off.
An extremely old set of samurai armour that is rusting away to nothing.
An extremely old set of samurai armour that is rusting away to nothing.
An extremely old set of samurai armour that is rusting away to nothing.
An extremely old set of samurai armour that is rusting away to nothing.

If a Hiver tries wearing a regular human-sized shirt it just sort of hangs loose and falls off their shoulders, often tangling up their arms.  So they were forced to manufacture their own, which they have done to a suspiciously higher standard than all their gear designed for humans.
Heavy prisoner shackles. They stop you from running and doing a lot of things. They also trip you up in combat. They are locked on, you need to pick the lock somehow.
This used to be a Holy Servant's robe, now reduced to rags.
A hat usually worn by weirdo assassins.  Hides the face and makes you look creepy.
Black rags typical of down-and-out hobo ninjas
Salvaged rags, straps and plates pulled together by a decent craftsman has made this monstrosity. Commonly found on wanderers and bandits, it shouldn't be underestimated.

Good shirt for sneaking about, doing spy stuff.
Traditional heavy duty armour commonly worn by government owned samurai.
A plated leather jacket with a good solid armour coverage. Commonly worn by the wealthier drifters and professional adventurer scouts.
A plated leather jacket with a good solid armour coverage. Commonly worn by the wealthier drifters and professional adventurer scouts.
Keeps the heat off your head and pads your brains.
The strange hat and stormgoggles of the Ashland drifters, strange individuals who have allegedly ventured into the Ashlands and returned, for reasons unknown.
A pair of stormgoggles of the Ashland drifters, strange individuals who have allegedly ventured into the Ashlands and returned, for reasons unknown.

A medium class leather armour, it's used to equip empire conscripts, partially because they don't usually have the endurance for wearing heavy samurai armour, but mainly because it's cheaper.  Not quite as good as mercenary leather armour.
A creepy black duster coat worn by wierdos out of the Ashlands.  The sleveless version is favoured by martial artists.
These rags are likely the shredded remains of some kind of uniform
Keeps sweat and hair out of your eyes.
Keeps sweat and hair out of your eyes.

Some mercenaries were interested in the capabilities of the Holy Nation's body armour, but didn't wan't the problems of appearing to be associated with the faction.  So they made their own copies without the religious faction logos painted all over it, and then blackened them in the forge.
